725525f-b.text:
Sixty-third Ave. (sidewalk thereon), at the S.W. corner of Queens Boulevard (automobiles thereon), showing the original Presbyterian Paraonage later known as the Thompson house. sales office. This is a set of two views.
May 1926.

727766f-d.text:
Queens Boulevard (formerly 287 Eoffman Boulevard), between Sixty-third Ave. (right) and 62nd Drive (left). This house was formerly on the north side of the old Oueens Boulevard Street line. When the street was widened it stood in the center thereof and because of this was either demolished or burned down. This is a set of four views. The occupants or owners were: M. Covert 1852-1860, Mrs. H. R. Covert 1873, Frost T. Covert Sr. 1873, and Frost T. Covert Jr.
April 1922.
Views 2 and 3: April 1923.
View 4: February 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

727767f-b.text:
Wueens Boulevard, west from 63rd Avenue. View 1 shows an old house, said to have been a parsonage,on the south side of the Boulevard. It is No. 9272 Cueens Boulevard. To tbue right are the old Thompson barns in rear of the Thompson farmhouse which later became
the Rego Park real estate office.
View 2 shows a more extensive view of the Boulevard. The house on the left is No. 9272, the one seewin view 1. The white house in the background is the pre-Revolutionary Thompson House. On the right is a pumping station. Cueens Boulevard is being widened; the buildings on the left mark the new building line and the new width
of the thoroughfare.
View 1: February, 1924
View 2: May, 19A6
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

727791f-c.text:
Queens Boulevard, north side, between Sixty-third Averue (foreground not shown) and 82nd Drive (background, not shown). At the right, beyornd the signboards is the M. Covert house of 1852-1860. Mrs. H. Covert was the owner in 1873. In the backoround, center, faintly distinguishable, is the home of Mrs. Howard. View No. 2 shows the Covert house oractically demolished. The new street line for Queens Boulevard will probably extend to a point beyond the house. Views 3 and 4 show a rear
of the house which is hidden bv an outhouse.
April 1923.
View 2: March 1925.
Views 334: February 8, 1924.
'gene L. Armbruster Collection
